ic forenames:  French Michel, Emile, Henri.","Altered form of French   Germain  .","French: from the feminine form of   Germain  . Compare   Germond  ."]},{"name":"Germundson","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Germundsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Germund</i> (see   Germond  )."]}]},{"name":"Lucia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the old Roman given name <i>Lucius</i>, which is probably a derivative of Latin <i>lux</i> ‘light’. The girl's name is common in Italy and elsewhere, and is found as a learned, Latinate doublet of   Lucy   in England.  St Lucia  of Syracuse, who was martyred in  304 , was a very popular saint in the Middle Ages; she is often represented in medieval art as blinded and with her eyes on a platter, but the tradition that she had her eyes put out is probably based on nothing more than the association between light and eyes."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucia Germonde was born in 1190, in Downham West, Norfolk, England, her father, John Germonde, was 26 and her mother, Eli